# Generation 291: relational TRANSITIVITY (basic-chat cat.7 prompt 123).
# "if A is bigger than B and B is bigger than C, is A bigger than C?" -> Yes.
#
# The transitivity is licensed by GRAMMAR: the comparative frame ("-er than", or
# analytic "more <adj> than") denotes a strict order, which is transitive — so it
# holds on the hermetic base with no per-relation fact. The reasoning is done by
# the ENGINE: the premise edges rel(x,y) plus the clause rel($A,$C):-rel($A,$B),
# rel($B,$C) are asserted to a scratch KB and the query is resolved by the same
# recursive binary join U3 (gen283) gave the solver — the binary transitive rule
# gen233 said the engine "can't carry" now runs as a real clause.

# Prompt 123, verbatim (uppercase variables lowercase-normalize to a/b/c).
> if A is bigger than B and B is bigger than C, is A bigger than C?
< Yes.
# The multi-sentence surface form, and a DIFFERENT comparative ("taller").
> a is taller than b. b is taller than c. is a taller than c?
< Yes.
# The ANALYTIC comparative "more <adj> than" (not just synthetic -er).
> if a is more beautiful than b and b is more beautiful than c, is a more beautiful than c?
< Yes.
# Honesty: a strict order is ASYMMETRIC — the reverse does not follow.
> if a is bigger than b and b is bigger than c, is c bigger than a?
< No.
# Honesty: two comparatives with no shared middle term do not chain; and mixing
# relations (bigger vs taller) is declined rather than silently coerced.
> if a is bigger than b and b is taller than c, is a bigger than c?
< I don't understand that yet.
